{{Use dmy dates|date=March 2014}}
'''The Forty Group''' was a Kenyan society or organisation of the mid-twentieth century constituted primarily of members of the [[Kenya African Union]] who joined with the aim of using violence to make their voice heard. The name is a translation of the [[Gikuyu language|Gĩkũyũ]] phrase '''Anake a 40''', which means '''The Young Men of 40'''. The organisation was also called '''Kiama kia 40''' translating to '''The [political] party of 40'''. The number 40 is a reference to the year 1940, in which most of the group's core members were [[Conscription|drafted]] into the British Armed Forces.

The organisation consisted mainly of men fresh from service in [[World War II]].

It was founded by [[Mwangi Macharia]] and gradually evolved into part of the [[Mau Mau]] rebellion of the 1950s.

[[Stanley Mathenge]] was one of the leaders of Forty Group.<ref name="clough">Marshall S. Clough: [https://books.google.com/books?id=jpbZEfiAPW0C&pg=PA130&dq=%22stanley+mathenge%22&as_brr=3&cd=2#v=onepage&q=%22stanley%20mathenge%22&f=false Mau Mau memoirs: history, memory, and politics] Lynne Rienner Publishers, 1998. {{ISBN|1-55587-537-8}}</ref>

