The '''Movement for Democracy and Progress''' (French: ''Mouvement pour la démocratie et le progrès'', MDP) is a [[political party]] in the [[Republic of the Congo]], led by [[Jean-Claude Ibovi]]. In the [[Republic of the Congo parliamentary election, 2007|parliamentary election]] held on June 24 and August 5, 2007, the party won one out of 137 seats.<ref>For detailed results see [[Republic of the Congo parliamentary election, 2007]] and [http://www.jeuneafrique.com/pays/congo_brazza/article_depeche.asp?art_cle=XIN70027lalliseriat0 "L'alliance présidentielle occupe 125 des 137 sièges parlementaires"], Xinhua, August 25, 2007 {{fr icon}}.</ref> It supports the government of President [[Denis Sassou Nguesso]].

Originally an organization called the National Convention for the Defense and Promotion of Denis Sassou Nguesso's Ideas (CNDPID), it was subsequently transformed into a new political party, the Movement for Democracy and Progress (MDP), which was officially launched on 18 February 2007 under Ibovi's leadership.<ref>Victor Kalenga Nsana, [http://fr.allafrica.com/stories/200702201121.html "Congo-Brazzaville: Sortie officielle du Mouvement pour la démocratie et le progrès"], ''Le Potentiel'', 20 February 2007 {{fr icon}}.</ref>

Ibovi was the only MDP candidate to obtain a seat in the National Assembly in the 2007 election.<ref>Séraphin Mabanza, ''Le Congo à l'ère de la Nouvelle Espérance: Réalités et perspectives'' (2009), L'Harmattan, page 167 {{fr icon}}.</ref>
